TY  - JOUR
T1  - Cognitive Style and DSS Design: A Comment on Huber's Paper
AU  - Robey, Daniel
Y1  - 1983/05/01
PY  - 1983
DA  - 1983/05/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.29.5.580
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.29.5.580
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 580
EP  - 582
VL  - 29
IS  - 5
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - The paper by Huber (Huber, G. P. 1983. Cognitive style as a basis for designing MIS and DSS: much ado about nothing? Management Sci. 29 (5) 567?579.) stimulates further comment. While his conclusions that cognitive styles research has not served and will not serve as a satisfactory basis for operational DSS design guidelines appear justified, some additional points need to be made. This paper looks at several of Huber's arguments more closely and suggests a potentially valuable role for cognitive style awareness in the DSS development process.
AB  - The paper by Huber (Huber, G. P. 1983. Cognitive style as a basis for designing MIS and DSS: much ado about nothing? Management Sci. 29 (5) 567?579.) stimulates further comment. While his conclusions that cognitive styles research has not served and will not serve as a satisfactory basis for operational DSS design guidelines appear justified, some additional points need to be made. This paper looks at several of Huber's arguments more closely and suggests a potentially valuable role for cognitive style awareness in the DSS development process.
SN  - 0025-1909
M3  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.29.5.580
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1287/mnsc.29.5.580
Y2  - 2024/03/28
